comments: It is somewhat challenging to rank equally vital concepts, to do with ocean health! It is hard to imagine how biodiversity and iconic animals can be preserved, if not for continued carbon storage by deep ocean and clean water, and coastal protection. It's difficult to imagine that tourism and food and non-food production can continue, without clean water and stable climate and coastlines. In the main, while I personally appreciate the incredible wealth from the ocean, and would be saddened to lose any of these benefits, humans have seemingly done their best to threaten the health of our oceans, lands, rivers, and climate. I'd give the vote to diverse other species over the thoughtless amongst our own species, who don't seem moved enough to consider sacrificing any personal conveniences, to save the health of the world that supports us.

comments: I fill out a lot of surveys. Most of them I don't really care about. This is a meaningful way to reach people who want to have a say. I've never felt like I could have a voice that would actually impact any real environmental issue so I hope the information here will help lobby the Federal and Provincial governments to make choices that preserve, protect and promote our oceanic provinces and communities. I have lived in Ontario, British Columbia and Nova Scotia and the coastal communities are by far the most beautiful in the country and are a big part of what makes us Canadians. The culture lies on the coasts. We need to protect them at all costs.

The Federal government does not care about our oceans and has no desire to align with other countries in order to protect marine fauna and maintain healthy fish stocks. Our government allows far too many fish to be extracted for commercial industries. In addition, one of the new omnibus bills rammed through by the Conservatives has extended moderate protection to commercially valuable species but removed any protection on species that are not commercially important. This is despicable and perfectly in line with the Harper Government's disgust for science and intelligence. Our oceans are in trouble and we're not doing anything at all to protect them.

comments: Cleanliness of the water is the most important thing in all this. Without it we will have none of the other things and neither will the aboriginals. The amount of plastics I have observed on beaches in North America is astounding. The minute plastic particles documented getting into the fish food supply is staggering. Carbon capture is overrated. Carbon dioxide is needed to sustain photosynthesis for plants to survive and produce oxygen and thus life itself. We each breathe out 2 lbs of CO2 per day,7B people, 14B lbs, 7M tons of CO2 produced each day by breathing alone, think about it. There is more methane released by earthquakes and volcanic eruptions than CO2 by man. Methane is 20x worse than CO2 as a greenhouse gas. Stop eating beef :)
